U.S. Unique Dialects in R

Jessica Blanton

2024-10-23

Our Question: What states have the most unique words as classified by the Dictionary of American Regional English?

Dataset obtained from www.kaggle.com

  • Rahimi, Afshin, Cohn, Trevor and Baldwin, Timothy. “A Neural Model for User Geolocation and Lexical Dialectology.” ACL 2017 (2017): 209.
  • Cassidy, F. G. (1985). Dictionary of American Regional English. Belknap Press of Harvard University Press.

Set your working directory to the place where you saved your downloaded files

setwd("[Enter your path here]")

# # Install and load useful magrittr package (Ceci n'est pas une pipe!)

Load packages for this R session

library(jsonlite)
library(magrittr)
library(tidyverse) #this includes "dplyr" and "ggplot2"
library(maps)
library(mapproj)
library(fiftystater)
# Import data
daredes <- fromJSON(txt = "geodare.json", simplifyVector = T)
# Expect this warning message:
#   JSON string contains (illegal) UTF8 byte-order-mark! 

# Tidy up column names
names(daredes) <- make.names(names(daredes))

# Make state index case-matchable
state.lc <- state.name%>%tolower() 

# Select only states from full DARE list (includes regions)
daredes.st <- daredes[(daredes$dialect)%in%state.lc,]

Look at words in some states of interest

daredes.st[daredes.st$dialect=="massachusetts",] %>% head
daredes.st[daredes.st$dialect=="ohio",] %>% head
daredes.st[daredes.st$dialect=="texas",] %>% head
daredes.st[daredes.st$dialect=="louisiana",] %>% head

Summarize the count of state-specific words, in decreasing order

daredes.count <- daredes.st%>%
  group_by(dialect)%>%
  summarize(count=n())%>%
  .[ order(.$count,decreasing = T),]

Look at states with largest count of unique words

Plot using ggplot2 & maps packages

Get plotting location data from maps package library

states <- map_data("state")

# Explore this "states" data frame
head(states,50)

Merge and sort

dialects.geo <- merge(states, daredes.count, sort = FALSE,
                      by.x = "region", by.y ="dialect", all.x = T)

dialects.geo <- dialects.geo[order(dialects.geo$count,decreasing = T), ]

# Check that no entries are missing between the merged tables
setdiff(states$region,dialects.geo$region)
setdiff(dialects.geo$region,states$region)

Plot the map with ggplot

Components of the visualization are mapped as layers

  • Coordinates
  • Statistics
  • Facets
  • Geometry
  • Aesthetics
  • Data

Let’s map this layer by layer to see how modifications to the intial figure are made

ggplot(dialects.geo, aes(long, lat)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(group = group, fill = count)) 

ggplot(dialects.geo, aes(long, lat)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(group = group, fill = count)) +
  scale_fill_continuous(high = "Navy", low = "#f7f7f7")

ggplot(dialects.geo, aes(long, lat)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(group = group, fill = count)) +
  scale_fill_continuous(high = "Navy", low = "#f7f7f7")+
  coord_map()

ggplot(dialects.geo, aes(long, lat)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(group = group, fill = count)) +
  scale_fill_continuous(high = "Navy", low = "#f7f7f7")+
  coord_map()+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", 
        panel.background = element_blank())

🤔 The maps package only shows the 48 contiguous states.

Plot all 50 states using the fiftystater package by Will Murphy: https://github.com/wmurphyrd

ggplot(daredes.count, aes(map_id = dialect)) + # map_id creates the aesthetic mapping to the state name column
  geom_map(aes(fill = count), map = fifty_states) + # map points to the fifty_states shape data
  expand_limits(x = fifty_states$long, y = fifty_states$lat) +
  coord_map() +
  scale_fill_continuous(high = "black", low = "#f7f7f7")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = NULL) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = NULL) +
  labs(x = "", y = "") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", 
        panel.background = element_blank())
